But since each square is part of two rectangles, and each rectangle is part of two squares, the graph is a collection of cycles. Let's see. For example, if we have a cycle of four nodes: square A connected to rectangle 1 and 2, square B connected to rectangle 2 and 3, square C connected to rectangle 3 and 4, square D connected to rectangle 4 and 1. Then, this forms a cycle of four squares and four rectangles. In such a case, the minimal vertex cover for a cycle with four nodes (even cycle) is 2, by selecting every other node. So, selecting two squares in the cycle would cover all edges. But in our case, how many cycles do we have? Let's see. After the first guess at the center, we have eight rectangles left. Each rectangle is connected to two squares. Let's try to visualize the graph. Each rectangle is an edge between two squares. So, the graph has eight edges (rectangles) and six nodes (squares: (1,1), (1,2), (1,3), (2,1), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3)). Wait, no, after the first guess at the center, the remaining squares are eight: (1,1), (1,2), (1,3), (2,1), (2,2) (but (2,2) is the center, which we already guessed), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3). Wait, no. Wait, the remaining eight squares are all the squares not in the center. So, (1,1), (1,2), (1,3), (2,1), (2,2) (but (2,2) is the center, which we already guessed), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3). Wait, no. Wait, the eight squares not in the center are: (1,1), (1,2), (1,3), (2,1), (2,3), (3,1), (3,2), (3,3). So, total eight squares. Each of these squares is part of two rectangles.
